{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DPYipVC6RzvC3rNbAEFo64","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive picture of the ingress-nginx configuration. Let me analyze the findings:\n\n**1. Controller Deployment (ingress-nginx-controller)**\n\nController args:\n- `--watch-ingress-without-class=true` (in last-applied annotation) AND `--watch-ingress-without-class=false` (in live spec) — there's a conflicting/duplicate flag. The live pod has both flags set, with `false` being the last value (which overrides `true` in most argument parsers). However, this is a configuration inconsistency.\n- `--publish-status-address=localhost` — sets the external IP to \"localhost\", which is a non-standard configuration that could be misleading for external clients.\n- `terminationGracePeriodSeconds: 0` — the controller can be terminated immediately without gracefully draining connections, risking dropped requests during restarts.\n\nThe security context looks mostly solid with non-root execution, dropped capabilities, and seccomp enabled, but the root filesystem isn't read-only, which is a security gap. The pod-level configuration appears to be cut off, but I should check what else might be misconfigured there.\n\nAt the pod level, the service account token is mounted by default, which gives the controller access to the Kubernetes API—necessary for watching Ingress resources, though it does expand the attack surface. The ConfigMap for the controller has no custom nginx configuration, so it's running with stock settings and no tuned timeouts or logging formats. Now I'm looking at the Ingress resources in the demo namespace to see how they're configured.\n\nThe `demo-app` Ingress routes traffic from `demo.example.com/app` to the backend service on port 80, with a rewrite rule to strip the path prefix, but it has no TLS, rate limiting, or authentication. The `rate-api` Ingress is more restrictive—it routes `rate.example.com/api` to its backend and applies rate limiting of 1 request per second with a burst multiplier of 1, returning 429 status codes when exceeded.\n\nThere's also a separate health check endpoint at `rate.example.com/health` that bypasses rate limiting entirely, plus a decoy Ingress at `rate-alt-easy.example.com/api` with no rate limiting at all to serve as a benchmark comparison. Finally, the `canary-stable` Ingress handles both health checks and root path requests for `canary.example.com`, routing them to a stable backend service.\n\nNow looking at the canary routing setup: there's a primary canary Ingress that uses the `X-Canary: always` header to send all matching requests to the canary backend, and a decoy canary Ingress that routes only requests with `X-Canary: beta` to its backend—though this one appears to have a configuration issue since it's missing a corresponding stable Ingress for the same host.\n\nThe controller is throwing an error because it can't merge the canary backend into a hostname that doesn't have a base Ingress defined. On the rate limiting side, there were some initial config issues with the burst parameter calculation that eventually resolved, but there's a discrepancy between the configured rejection code (429) and what's actually appearing in the logs (503). The 503 responses instead of 429s suggest the reject code annotation wasn't properly applied when it was patched in after the initial deployment, or there's a timing issue where the config change didn't fully propagate before traffic started hitting the rate limiter. The sequence shows annotations were added post-creation, triggering a reload that initially failed with the burst=0 error, then eventually succeeded—but the response codes don't match what the annotation should enforce. The annotations were added via `kubectl annotate` after the initial creation, which is why they appear in the live config but not in the last-applied configuration. Looking at the actual logs, I see successful 200 responses followed by a 503, which suggests the rate limiter is rejecting with 503 instead of the expected 429 code—possibly because the `limit-reject-code` annotation support depends on the controller version or wasn't properly applied to the generated nginx config.\n\nNow I'm compiling the key findings, starting with the conflicting `--watch-ingress-without-class` flags in the Deployment spec.\n\nThe controller has both `true` and `false` values for this flag, with the `false` taking precedence, but this indicates a configuration management issue where a patch was applied on top of the original config without properly reconciling the state.\n\nThe `terminationGracePeriodSeconds` is set to 0, which means pods are killed immediately during rolling updates without allowing in-flight requests to complete—this needs to be at least 30 seconds in production, ideally paired with a `preStop` lifecycle hook.\n\nThe `readOnlyRootFilesystem` is disabled in the security context...\n\nThe main nginx ConfigMap is empty with no custom settings, so there's no security hardening at the nginx level like hiding the version or configuring SSL parameters.\n\nAll Ingress resources are HTTP-only with no TLS configured, leaving traffic unencrypted.\n\nThe rate-api Ingress has a mismatch where the annotation specifies a 429 reject code but nginx is actually returning 503 responses, suggesting the annotation isn't being applied correctly and clients get a misleading error code.\n\nWhen rate-api combined a limit of 1 RPS with a burst multiplier of 1, it generated an invalid nginx config with burst=0, which caused reload failures until the controller eventually resolved to a working configuration — this shows the annotation values weren't validated before being applied.\n\nThere's also a decoy Ingress called rate-api-alt-easy that bypasses rate limiting entirely.\n\nThe canary-alt Ingress is broken because it's marked as a canary route but there's no primary Ingress for that host, so the controller can't merge the canary backend and keeps logging errors about the missing hostname.\n\nEven though canary-alt is labeled as a decoy, it's actively causing controller reconciliation failures and should be removed or fixed. None of the Ingress resources have any authentication configured, leaving all endpoints publicly accessible. The controller reports Ingress status as localhost, which is fine for a local cluster setup.\n\nThe controller runs as a single replica with no autoscaling, creating a single point of failure for all ingress traffic. I'm also digging deeper into the canary configuration — specifically how `canary-by-header-value: always` works in nginx-ingress, which appears to route all requests with the X-Canary header to the canary backend regardless of the header value.\n\nNow I'll compile all these findings into a comprehensive text document.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":20427,"cache_read_input_tokens":30658,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":20427},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cfa6a4e8-867e-4134-bd3d-7443bc7bce85","uuid":"8e579e2d-8cb7-4697-afab-eb954613971f","request_id":"req_011CcQ4YJ4vnP5VMCxrRv1Yk"}
